{{See also|Amedzofe, Ghana}}

In [[Ewe (people)|Ewe]] oral history, '''Amedzofe''' ({{IPA-ee|amedzoɸɛ|lang}}),{{Fix|text=missing tone}} literally 'origin/home of humanity', is one of the names for [[Ketu (Benin)|Ketu]]. Ketu, in present-day [[Benin]], was a central place in the history of the [[Gbe languages|Gbe]] peoples. The Gbe peoples originally were part of the [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] [[Oyo Empire|Oyo]] people of [[Nigeria]], but they were pressed westward by a series of wars between the 10th and the 13th century. In Ketu, the ancestors of the Gbe-speaking peoples separated themselves from other refugees and began to establish their own identity.

