[[File:Swami Vivekananda 1893 Scanned Image.jpg|right|250px|thumb|upright|Swami Vivekananda]]
'''[[Swami Vivekananda]]''', the nineteenth-century Indian [[Hindu]] [[monk]] is considered as one of the most influential people of modern India and [[Hinduism]]. [[Rabindranath Tagore]] suggested to study Vivekananda's works to learn about India. Indian independence activist [[Subhas Chandra Bose]] regarded Vivekananda as his spiritual teacher. [[Mahatma Gandhi]] said that after reading the works of Vivekananda his love for his nation became a thousand-fold.

[[Barack Obama]], the President of the United States quoted Vivekananda's words in his speech delivered in India in November 2010. [[Jayalalitha]], the Chief Minister of [[Tamil Nadu]] said that Vivekananda inspired her to enter politics. 

Vivekananda's birthday, on 12 January is celebrated as the [[National Youth Day]] in India. In 2012, a three-day [[150th birth anniversary of Swami Vivekananda#World Congress of Religions 2012|world conference]] was organised by the Institute of World Religions to commemorate the [[150th birth anniversary of Swami Vivekananda]] to mark the days Vivekananda delivered his historic lectures in 1893. In 2013, [[Indian railways]] started [[Vivek Express]], four pairs of express trains as a tribute to Vivekananda on his 150th birth anniversary.

== Influence on notable Indian people ==
Vivekananda, after he became a "sannyasin of high intellect, action, and devotion" in 1886, had a deep desire to spread the message of “divine unity of existence and unity in diversity’ throughout the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.oocities.org/neovedanta/sv8.html|title= Life and Teachings of Swami Vivekananda: Part 7 The Soul Wanted to Soar High|accessdate=29 September 2013|publisher=International Forum for NeoVedantins}}</ref> Vivekananda then as a ''Parivrajaka'', meaning: "a wandering monk", travelled the length and breadth of the country. For nearly two years, he travelled  all over India  from north to west, and befriended many notable people and influenced them with his Vedanta philosophy and many of them even encouraged and supported him to travel to the US to attend the Parliament of World Religions in Chicago; some of the prominent names are [[Ajit Singh of Khetri]] of [[Rajasthan]], Dewan of Porbandar and Junagadh in Gujarat, Raja of Ramnad of Madras,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oocities.org/neovedanta/sv9.html|title=Life and Teachings of Swami Vivekananda: Part 8:Parivrajaka Sadhu: The 'wandering monk'|accessdate=29 September 2013|publisher=International Forum for NeoVedantins}}</ref> [[K. Seshadri Iyer]], Dewan of Mysore and [[Chamaraja Wodeyar]], the [[Maharaja of Mysore]].<ref name="Chattopadhyaya1999">{{cite book|author=Rajagopal Chattopadhyaya|title=Swami Vivekananda in India: A Corrective Biography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EtcoeaQIQdAC&pg=PA95|accessdate=29 September 2013|date=1 January 1999|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publ.|isbn=978-81-208-1586-5|pages=95–}}</ref>
{{Double image|left| Bal G. Tilak.jpg|190| MKGandhi.jpg|220|Left: Bal Gangadhar Tilak (1856–1920) said that Swami Vivekananda preached Hindu religion in the length and breadth of the world. Right: Mahatma Gandhi said that after reading the works of Vivekananda, his love for his nation became a thousand-fold.}}

[[Bal Gangadhar Tilak]], the Indian nationalist, journalist, teacher, social reformer, lawyer and an independence activist who was the first popular leader of the Indian Independence Movement observed :”Twelve centuries ago Sankaracharya was the only great personality, who not only spoke of the purity of our religion, not only uttered in words that this religion was our strength and wealth, not only said that it was our sacred duty to preach this religion in the length and breadth of the world&nbsp;– but also brought all this into action. Swami Vivekananda is a person of that stature—who appeared towards the last half of the 19th century."
<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.slideshare.net/dokka/great-indian-personalities-thoughtrs-on-swami-vivekananda|title=Great indian personalities thoughtrs on Swami Vivekananda|accessdate=25 March 2012|publisher=Slideshare.net}}</ref>

[[Rabindranath Tagore]] suggested "If you want to know India, study Vivekananda. In him everything is positive and nothing negative."{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|p=196}} [[Sri Aurobindo]] has said: "Vivekananda was a soul of puissance if ever there was one, a very lion among men, but the definite work he has left behind is quite incommensurate with our impression of his creative might and energy.{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|p=197}} [[Brahmabandhav Upadhyay]] told, Vivekananda and his mission encouraged him to go to England and propagate Hinduism and [[Vedanta]] there. [[Bal Gangadhar Tilak]] praised Vivekananda for taking the responsibility to re-establish the glory of Hinduism.{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|pp=198–199}} [[Bipin Chandra Pal]] felt, Vivekananda's message was "the message of modern humanity".{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|pp=201–203}}

On 6 February 1921, [[Mahatma Gandhi]] came to [[Belur Math]] and paid homage to Vivekananda. On this occasion he said: {{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|p=206}}
<blockquote>I have come here to pay my homage and respect to the revered memory of Swami Vivekananda, whose birthday is being celebrated today. I have gone through his works very thoroughly, and after having gone through them, the love that I had for my country became a thousand-fold.<ref name=swamigov>{{cite web|title=about Swami Vivekananda|url=http://vivekananda.gujarat.gov.in/influence.aspx|publisher=Gujurat.gov|accessdate=18 October 2013}}</ref> I ask you, young men, not to go away empty-handed without imbibing something of the spirit of the place where Swami Vivekananda lived and died.</blockquote>

He also told that Vivekananda's writings needed no introduction.<ref name=MGquote>{{cite web|title=Mahatma Gandhis'q quotes on Swami Vivekananda|url=http://www.swamivivekanandaquotes.org/2013/11/mahatma-gandhis-quotes-and-comments-on.html|publisher=Swami Vivekananda Quotes|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>

In 1893, during the journey from [[Yokohama]] to Canada on the ship ''Empress'', Vivekananda accidentally met [[Jamsetji Tata]] who was also going to Chicago. During the conversation Vivekananda told Tata about the necessity of establishing a world class scientific Institution in India and this encouraged Tata to establish the [[Indian Institute of Science]], which gradually became one of India's best-known research university of India.{{Sfn|Rajadhyaksha|2007|p=31}} [[Jawaharlal Nehru]], the first Prime Minister of [[Independent India]], praised Vivekananda's personality and dignity and said that his heart carried fire: "it was no empty talk he was indulging in. He was putting his heart and soul into the words he uttered." Nehru also recounted that "his generation" was widely influenced by Vivekananda.{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|p=206}}

{{Double image|right| Rabindranath Tagore in 1909.jpg|200|C Rajagopalachari Feb 17 2011.JPG|200|Left: Rabindranath Tagore (left) suggested to read Vivekananda's writing to learn about India. Right: C Rajagopalachari told, Vivekananda saved Hinduism and India.}}
Indian independence activist [[Subhas Chandra Bose]] considered Vivekananda as his spiritual teacher. He called Vivekananda a "full-blooded masculine personality&nbsp;– and a fighter to the core of being". Bose told, under the "sacred influence" of [[Ramakrishna]] and Vivekananda his own life got awakened.{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|pp=209–210}}

[[Vinoba Bhave]] praised Vivekananda's contribution to make Indians' conscious of their strength and said that he showed them their shortcomings and defects and taught them to overcome these. He further mentioned that at the time of Vivekananda people of India were shrouded in ''[[tamas (philosophy)|tamas]]'', ignorance and unwisdom, and failed to distinguish between weakness and non-attachment and peace. In such a situation Vivekananda brought new light and he taught "The same Soul resides in each and all" and suggested to serve mankind considering them manifestations of God ''[[daridranarayan]]'' (meaning: "poverty stricken god").{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|pp=211–212}}

According to Indian independence activist and social worker [[C. Rajagopalachari]] who became the first Indian [[Governor General of India]], Vivekananda saved Hinduism and India.{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|p=218}} He stated that we owe everything to Vivekananda. The first Vice-President and the second President of independent India [[Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan]] said that Vivekananda's was born in a "critical period" when the nation and her people were collapsing in "despair, frustration and hopelessness" and in such circumstances Vivekananda's teachings gave them new hope and taught them to rely on spiritual resources.{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|pp=218–219}} Indian historian Ramesh Chandra Majumdar told, Vivekananda preached the best parts of Hinduism and Indian spirituality to the world.{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|p=220}} According to Majumdar's studies, Vivekananda's ideals added spiritual basis in the Indian nationalism. Majumdar also noted, though Vivekananda was an ascetic, his patriotism was remarkable. He said:{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|p=221}}

<blockquote>Though an ascetic, Vivekananda was a patriot of patriots. The thought of restoring the prehistoric glory of India by resuscitating among her people the spiritual vitality which was dormant, but not dead, was always the uppermost though in his mind...</blockquote>

[[Pranab Mukherjee]], the President of India, suggested in a speech delivered on 31 May 2013 at the Convocation Hall, University of Mumbai, Mumbai, to remember the call of Vivekananda to reconstruct India's national character. He also told :—
<blockquote> Swamiji unhesitatingly appreciated the positive aspects and accomplishments of the Western Societies&nbsp;– and refrained from being dogmatic as he made his point, he was able to build a robust new bridge of understanding and goodwill for India. In so doing, he also opened a new dialogue between our peoples based on mutual acceptance.<ref name="Pranamb Mukherjee's speech May 2013">{{cite web|title=Pranamb Mukherjee's speech May 2013 |url=http://presidentofindia.gov.in/sp310513-1.html |publisher=Indian Government |accessdate=29 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130929111837/http://presidentofindia.gov.in/sp310513-1.html |archivedate=29 September 2013 |deadurl=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref></blockquote>

[[Narendra Modi]], the Prime minister of India, is an ardent admirer of Vivekananda. In April 2013, he visited [[Belur Math]] and meditated at the room of Vivekananda.<ref name="Modi meditates OneIndia">{{cite news|title=Narendra Modi meditates in Vivekananda's room in Kolkata |url=http://news.oneindia.in/2013/04/10/narendra-modi-meditates-in-vivekananda-s-room-kolkata-1190491.html |accessdate=28 September 2013 |newspaper=One India |date=10 April 2013 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130928184549/http://news.oneindia.in/2013/04/10/narendra-modi-meditates-in-vivekananda-s-room-kolkata-1190491.html |archivedate=28 September 2013 |deadurl=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Jayalalithaa]], the Chief Minister of [[Tamil Nadu]] told, Vivekananda inspired her to enter politics. She said:<ref name="Jayalalithaa's inspiration">{{cite news|title=Vivekananda my inspiration to enter politics: Jayalalithaa |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil_nadu/article1481716.ece |accessdate=28 September 2013 |newspaper=The New Indian Express |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130928185116/http://newindianexpress.com/states/tamil_nadu/article1481716.ece |archivedate=28 September 2013 |deadurl=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

<blockquote> She further said that there are "some people who made public life a profession. The profession can be transformed into service, but service cannot be turned into a profession. As far as I am concerned, Swami Vivekananda was a great inspiration for me to enter politics. When I took the first step into politics in 1982, I mentioned Swami Vivekananda in an interview."</blockquote>

[[Mamata Banerjee]], the Chief Minister of [[West Bengal]] was inspired by Vivekananda's writings which she said helped her in the difficult times of her political career. Banerjee stated:<ref name="Mamat Banerjee drew inspiration">{{cite news|title=Mamata drew inspiration from Vivekananda |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/mamata-drew-inspiration-from-vivekananda/article4300918.ece |accessdate=28 September 2013 |newspaper=The Hindu |date=12 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130928185747/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/mamata-drew-inspiration-from-vivekananda/article4300918.ece |archivedate=28 September 2013 |deadurl=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

<blockquote>In the course of the several movements that I led, there would be moments of doubt. There were some who were critical of me and even I wondered that there were so many people who had pinned their hopes on me. What if I were to fail them? I would read books written by Swami Vivekananda to gather my strength.</blockquote>

In 2013, [[Yoga]] [[guru]] [[Ramdev]] told he feels Vivekananda spread "India's cultural message" to the world.<ref name="Ramdev's comment">{{cite news|title=Vivekananda gave India's cultural message to world: Ramdev |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/1896086/report-vivekananda-gave-india-s-cultural-message-to-world-ramdev |accessdate=2 October 2013 |newspaper=Daily News and Analysis |date=30 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131002001629/http://www.dnaindia.com/india/1896086/report-vivekananda-gave-india-s-cultural-message-to-world-ramdev |archivedate=2 October 2013 |deadurl=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

Social activist [[Anna Hazare]] was motivated by the works of Swami Vivekananda and took inspiration for all the social work he did from Swami Vivekananda only.<ref name="Anna Hazare On Swami Vivekananda">{{cite web|title=Anna Hazare On Swami Vivekananda|url=http://www.swamivivekanandaquotes.org/2014/04/anna-hazare-on-swami-vivekananda.html|publisher=Swami Vivekananda Quotes|accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref>

[[Arvind Kejriwal]] read about Swami Vivekananda during his [[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur|IIT]] days and was very much inspired from him.

[[Kangana Ranaut]] considers Swami Vivekananda as her Spiritual Guru and is an ardent follower of his teachings.

== Influence on non-Indian people ==
Vivekananda, during and after his tour of western countries in Europe and the United States had profound influence on notable personalities, who either became his ardent devotees or friends and some even his ardent disciples and many of whom even became ascetics. Right at the beginning of his visit to Chicago to address the Parliament of World Religions Professor [[John Henry Wright]] of [[Harvard University]], invited him to speak at Harvard.<ref name="wright">{{Harvnb|Minor|1986|p=133}}</ref> He pointed out to Vivekananda the necessity of going to the Parliament of Religions, which he thought would give an introduction to the nation.<ref name="Bhuyan 2003 16"/> Wright's reasoning was "To ask for your credentials is like asking the sun to state its right to shine in the heavens".<ref name="Bhuyan 2003 16">{{Harvnb|Bhuyan|2003|p = 16}}</ref> Some of such well-known luminaries are: [[Max Müller]] (Indologist), [[J. J. Goodwin]], [[John Henry Barrows]], [[Mark Twain]], Sturdy, [[Romain Rolland]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ramakrishnavivekananda.info/vivekananda_biography/11_northern_india.htm|title= In Northern India|accessdate=29 September 2013|publisher= Ramakrishnavivekananda.info}}</ref>
[[Sara Chapman Bull]], his American mother and benefactor, [[Mary Hale]], [[Josephine MacLeod]], Christine Greenstidel (who later came to be known as [[Sister Christine]]), Maragaret Noble ([[Sister Nivedita]] in later years), [[William James]], [[Josiah Royce]], [[Robert G. Ingersoll]], [[Nikola Tesla]], [[Lord Kelvin]], [[Harriet Monroe]], [[Ella Wheeler Wilcox]], [[Sarah Bernhardt]], [[Emma Calvé]] and [[Hermann Ludwig Ferdinand von Helmholtz]] {{sfn|Badrinath|2006|p=x}} He initiated several followers : Marie Louise (a French woman) became [[Swami Abhayananda]], and Leon Landsberg became Swami Kripananda,<ref name="bruke-618">{{Harvnb|Burke|1958|p=618}}</ref>

American industrialist [[John D. Rockefeller]] reportedly made his first large donation for public welfare and later became a notable philanthropist after a meeting with Vivekananda. Vivekananda succinctly explained to Rockfeller that his philanthropy would only be a channel to help the poor and distressed people.{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|p=178}}

Vivekananda influenced French Opera singer [[Emma Calvé]], who wrote in her autobiography:{{Sfn|Calvé|1922|p=185}}

<blockquote>It has been my good fortune and my joy to know a man who truly "walked with God," a noble being, a saint, a philosopher, and a true friend. His influence upon my spiritual life was profound. He opened up new horizons before me, enlarging and vivifying my religious ideas and ideals, teaching me a broader understanding of truth. My soul will bear him an eternal gratitude.</blockquote>

Vivekananda's life and works have influenced many scholars, writers, politicians worldwide. French writer [[Romain Rolland]] wrote that Vivekananda was "energy personified". Rolland felt "kingliness" was Vivekananda's characteristics, "He was a born king and nobody ever came near him in India or America without paying homage to his majesty."{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|p=212}} American writer, historian, philosopher [[Will Durant]] told, the speeches of Vivekananda were more "virile" than the ones delivered in the Vedic times.{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|p=218}}

The nationalist leader and the first president of independent Indonesia [[Sukarno]] said that it was Swami Vivekananda who inspired him to become strong and to serve God and mankind.{{Sfn|Grover|2000|p=479}} Historian and [[Indologist]] [[Arthur Llewellyn Basham]] compared Vivekananda with other eminent religious figures of India such as [[Kabir]], [[Adi Shankara]], [[Chaitanya Mahaprabhu|Chaitanya]].{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|p=218}} Russian academician and public figure [[Eugene Chelyshev]] was an ardent admirer of Swami Vivekananda. He said:{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|p=226}}
<blockquote>Reading and re-reading the works of Vivekananda each time I find in them something new that helps deeper to understand India, its philosophy, the way of the life and customs of the people in the past and the present, their dreams of the future...</blockquote>
Chelyshev also predicted that the memory of Vivekananda will never fade away.{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|p=227}} Chinese scholar Huan Xin Chuan stated that Vivekananda was the most renowned social figure of modern China and Chinese socialists carefully study the works of Vivekananda.{{Sfn|Vivekananda|Lokeswarananda|1996|p=228}}

[[Barack Obama]], the President of the United States, quoted Vivekananda's words in his speech delivered in India in November 2010. He said:<ref name="US President Barack Obama’s Parliament address">{{cite news|title=U.S. President Barack Obama's Parliament address |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/us-president-barack-obamas-parliament-address/article874394.ece |accessdate=28 September 2013 |newspaper=The Hindu |date=8 November 2010 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130928195753/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/us-president-barack-obamas-parliament-address/article874394.ece |archivedate=28 September 2013 |deadurl=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

<blockquote>Instead of succumbing to division, you have shown that the strength of India—the very idea of India—is its embrace of all colors, castes and creeds. It's the diversity represented in this chamber today. It's the richness of faiths celebrated by a visitor to my hometown of Chicago more than a century ago—the renowned Swami Vivekananda. He said that, "holiness, purity and charity are not the exclusive possessions of any church in the world, and that every system has produced men and women of the most exalted character."</blockquote>

== Notable memorials and observations ==

=== National Youth Day ===
{{Main|National Youth Day (India)}}
Swami Vivekananda's birthday, i.e. 12 January, is celebrated as the [[National Youth Day]] in India. On 17 October 1984, the Indian Government officially declared the birth date of Vivekananda as the National Youth Day, which was to be celebrated 1985 onwards. The circular stated: "it was felt that the philosophy of Swamiji and the ideals for which he lived and worked could be a great source of inspiration for the Indian Youth."{{Sfn|Goel|2008|p=103}}

=== World Brotherhood Day ===
The "World Brotherhood Day" is observed on 11 September, on the day when Vivekananda delivered his first speech at the [[Parliament of the World's Religions]] Chicago in 1893 and addressed the American people and his audience as "Sisters and brothers of America".<ref name="A saffron monk who introduced India to the world">{{cite news|title=A saffron monk who introduced India to the world |url=http://zeenews.india.com/blog/a-saffron-monk-who-introduced-india-to-the-world_251.html |accessdate=28 September 2013 |newspaper=Zee News |date=11 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130928201222/http://zeenews.india.com/blog/a-saffron-monk-who-introduced-india-to-the-world_251.html |archivedate=28 September 2013 |deadurl=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

=== 150th birth anniversary of Swami Vivekananda ===
The [[150th birth anniversary of Swami Vivekananda]] was celebrated in India and abroad during 2013. The Ministry of Youth Affairs and Sports in India officially made an official declaration in this regard.<ref name="PTI declaration">{{cite web|title=2013–14 Declared the Year for Skill Development of the Youth Parliamentary Consultative Committee Attached to Ministry of Youth Affairs & Sports Meets|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/erelease.aspx?relid=92824|publisher=PTI|accessdate=3 March 2013}}</ref> Year-long events and programs have been organised by branches of the [[Ramakrishna Math]], the [[Ramakrishna Mission]], the central and state governments in India, educational institutions and youth groups. Bengali film director Tutu (Utpal) Sinha made a film, ''[[The Light: Swami Vivekananda]]'', and Indian American Bengali animator and laserist [[Manick Sorcar]] created a laser show, ''[[Swamiji (film)|Swamiji]]'',<ref name="Swamiji">{{cite web|title=Swami Vivekananda’s life depicted in laser|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/features/swami-vivekanandas-life-depicted-in-laser/article3988155.ece|publisher=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref> as a tribute for his 150th birth anniversary.<ref name="Year-long events to mark Vivekananda's 150th birthday">{{cite news|title=Year-long events to mark Vivekananda's 150th birthday|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-01-05/mumbai/36160847_1_ramakrishna-mission-sachin-pilot-tripura-governor|accessdate=29 September 2013|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref>

Swami Vivekananda delivered his famous lectures at the Parliament of the World's Religions, Chicago in 1893. In 2012, a 3-day World conference was organised by the Institute of World Religions (of the [[List of Hindu temples in the United States|Washington Kali Temple]]), [[Burtonsville, Maryland]], in association with the Council for Parliament of World Religions, Chicago, [[Illinois]] to commemorate the 150th birth anniversary of Swami Vivekananda.<ref name="World Congress of Religions 2012">{{cite web |title=World Congress of Religions 2012 |url=http://www.parliamentofreligions.org/news/index.php/2012/09/world-congress-of-religions-2012/ |publisher=Parliament of the World's Religions |accessdate=28 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130928190128/http://www.parliamentofreligions.org/news/index.php/2012/09/world-congress-of-religions-2012/ |archivedate=28 September 2013 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

=== Vivek Express ===
In 2011—2013 [[Railway Budget]], [[Indian railways]] announced four pairs of new express trains on the Indian Railways network. These new trains were started as a tribute to Vivekananda on his 140th birth anniversary.<ref name="Salient Features of New all India Time Table ‘Trains at a Glance’">{{cite web|title=Salient Features of New all India Time Table 'Trains at a Glance' |url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/erelease.aspx?relid=72959 |publisher=Press Information Bureau, India |accessdate=29 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130929112527/http://pib.nic.in/newsite/erelease.aspx?relid=72959 |archivedate=29 September 2013 |deadurl=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

=== Public Notice 3 ===
To mark the anniversary of Swami Vivekananda's landmark address at the Chicago Art Institute, and in remembrance of the terrorist attacks at the World Trade Center and the Pentagon 108 years later on that very date, September 11, Indian artist Jitish Kallat created Public Notice 3, a site-specific installation on the Art Institute's Woman's Board Grand Staircase.

On January 28, 2012, the Art Institute of Chicago, in conjunction with the Republic of India, reinstalled a plaque commemorating Vivekananda's landmark speech outside Fullerton Hall.<ref>http://www.artic.edu/about/mission-and-history/1879-1913-formative-years/1893-world-s-parliament-religions-and-swami/ref</ref>

== In popular culture ==

=== Films ===
Bengali
Swami Vivekananda has been the primary topic of many films, dramas ad folk-plays. Bengali film director [[Amar Mullick]] made two different movies: [[Swamiji (film)|Swamiji]] (1949) and its adaptation in Hindi, ''[[Swami Vivekananda (1955 film)|Swami Vivekananda]]'' (1955). The film ''Swami Vivekananda'' (1955) is considered a "faithful and memorable documentation feature" on Vivekananda.<ref name="Indian Express Take a little">{{cite news|title=Take a little, leave most behind... |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/take-a-little-leave-most-behind.../1074204/0 |accessdate=26 September 2013 |newspaper=The Indian Express |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130926024421/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/take-a-little-leave-most-behind.../1074204/ |archivedate=26 September 2013 |deadurl=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

The ''[[Swami Vivekananda (1998 film)|Swami Vivekananda]]'' was released on 12 June 1998. The film was premiered on India's public service broadcaster Doordarshan on 15 August 1998 as a part of Doordarshan's celebration of 50th year of India's Independence.<ref name="Iyer submits to Ramakrishna Mission to release Vivekananda">{{cite news |title=Iyer submits to Ramakrishna Mission to release Vivekananda |url=http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/ie/daily/19980815/22750354.html |accessdate=5 September 2013 |newspaper=Indian Express |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6JOgV4b4i?url=http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/ie/daily/19980815/22750354.html |archivedate=5 September 2013 |deadurl=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The film has been appreciated for blending the role of "eccentric middle-aged mystic, nominally a Brahmin priest, claiming nothing short of godhood role “ of Paramahmsa very well with that of the “ young non-Brahmin agnostic modernist role" of Vivekananda.<ref name="India Today June 1998">{{cite news |title=All-pervasive intolerance forces director of Swami Vivekananda to make seminal changes to cast and script of the historical film |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/intolerance-forces-director-of-swami-vivekananda-to-make-seminal-changes-to-cast-and-script-of-historical-film/1/264713.html |accessdate=5 September 2013 |newspaper=India Today |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6JOhboqhM?url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/intolerance-forces-director-of-swami-vivekananda-to-make-seminal-changes-to-cast-and-script-of-historical-film/1/264713.html |archivedate=5 September 2013 |deadurl=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

In 2013, Utpal (Tutu) Sinha directed ''[[The Light: Swami Vivekananda]]'' which was a tribute to Vivekananda on his 150th anniversary of his birth.<ref name="Embrace a good way of living">{{cite news|title=Embrace a good way of living|url=http://portal.thebengalpost.com/index.php/index/newsdetails/Embrace-a-good-way-of-living-419310111357823535|accessdate=24 September|newspaper=Bengal Post}}</ref><ref name="I am inspired by Rekhaji: Archita Sahu">{{cite news|title=I am inspired by Rekhaji: Archita Sahu|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-09/news-interviews/32140031_1_odia-odisha-mujra|accessdate=24 September 2013|newspaper=The Times of India|date=9 June 2012}}</ref><ref name="TW The Light – Swami Vivekananda">{{cite web|title=The Light – Swami Vivekananda|url=http://tollywoodindustry.com/the-light-swami-vivekananda/|accessdate=24 September 2013}}</ref>  Indian American Bengali animator and laserist [[Manick Sorcar]] created a laser show, ''[[Swamiji (film)|Swamiji]]'',<ref name="Swamiji" /> in honor of the anniversary.

=== Dramas ===
Bengali theatre group ''Lokkrishti'' staged a drama ''[[Biley]]'' to commemorate the birth anniversary. Bengali theatre actor [[Debshankar Haldar]] played the role of Swami Vivekananda in this drama.<ref name="THeatre review Biley">{{cite news|title=THeatre review Biley |url=http://my.anandabazar.com/content/%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%9F%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF-%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B2%E0%A7%8B%E0%A6%9A%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BE-38 |accessdate=4 March 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121115194302/http://my.anandabazar.com/content/%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%9F%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF-%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B2%E0%A7%8B%E0%A6%9A%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BE-38 |archivedate=15 November 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2013 ''Belgharia Shankhamala theatre group'' staged the drama ''[[Bireswar]]''. The drama was written by Basab Dasgupta and directed by Debesh Chattopadhyay.<ref name="Bireswar drama review">{{cite web |title=মন নিকেতন (Bireswar drama review) |url=http://my.anandabazar.com/content/%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%9F%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF-%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B2%E0%A7%8B%E0%A6%9A%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BE-69 |publisher=[[Anandabazar Patrika]] |accessdate=29 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130929111211/http://my.anandabazar.com/content/%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%9F%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF-%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B2%E0%A7%8B%E0%A6%9A%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BE-69 |archivedate=29 September 2013 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

