{{more footnotes|date=March 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}
'''Ranajit Guha''' (born Siddhakati, [[Backergunje]], 23 May 1923) is a historian of [[South Asia]] who was very greatly influential in the [[Subaltern studies|Subaltern Studies group]],<ref>{{Cite book | first=Ranajit |last=Guha |title=Subaltern Studies Reader, 1986-1995 |isbn=0-8166-2759-2|publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1993}}</ref> and was the editor of several of the group's early [[anthology|anthologies]]. He migrated from [[India]] to the [[United Kingdom|UK]] in 1959, and was a reader in history at the [[University of Sussex]]. He currently lives in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sai.uni-heidelberg.de/history/download/ranajit_guha_interview_2.2.11.pdf | title = In Search of Transcendence: An Interview with Ranajit Guha | accessdate = 26 February 2011 | author = Milinda Banerjee | publisher = [[University of Heidelberg]]}}</ref> Guha rose to prominence at the [[University of Sussex]] and then moved to the [[Australian National University]] where he continued the work on subaltern studies.
His ''Elementary Aspects of Peasant Insurgency in Colonial India'' is widely considered to be a classic.<ref>{{Cite news |page=200 | first=Amrita |last=Biswas |title=Research Note on Subaltern Studies |publisher=Journal of Literature, Culture and Media Studies |year=2009}}</ref> Aside from this, his founding statement in the first volume of Subaltern Studies set the agenda for the [[Subaltern studies|Subaltern Studies group]], defining the "subaltern" as "the demographic difference between the total Indian population and all those whom we have described as the ‘elite’."<ref>{{Cite news |pages=1–8 | first=Ranajit |last=Guha |title=On Some Apects of the Historiography of Colonial India |publisher=Subaltern Studies |year=1982}}</ref>
